<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun5-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>FUN-5 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given <m>f(x,y)=\ln(x^2+y^2)</m></p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the domain of <m>f(x,y)</m> using correct set notation.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The natural logarithm is only defined for positive arguments.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\{(x,y) \in \mathbb{R}^2 : x^2+y^2 > 0\}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>The argument of the natural logarithm must be positive:</p>
          <p><m>x^2+y^2 > 0</m>.</p>
          <p>This describes all points in the plane except the origin.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Evaluate <m>f(2e,e)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To evaluate <m>f(2e,e)</m>, substitute <m>x=2e</m> and <m>y=e</m> into the function.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>f(2e,e)=\ln(5)+2</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>To evaluate <m>f(2e,e)</m>, substitute <m>x=2e</m> and <m>y=e</m> into the function:</p>
          <p><m>f(2e,e)=\ln((2e)^2+e^2)=\ln(4e^2+e^2)=\ln(5e^2)=\ln(5)+\ln(e^2)=\ln(5)+2</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given <m>f(x,y)=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m></p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find and sketch the level curve of when <m>c=0</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set <m>f(x,y)=c</m> and solve for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The level curve is the point <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>
        <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-fun5a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-2,-2,2,2)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <point p="(0,0)" alignment="ne">(0,0)</point>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph is the point (0,0).">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        <solution><p>Setting <m>f(x,y)=0</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=0</m>.</p>
          <p>This implies <m>x^2+y^2=0</m>, which is only satisfied when <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=0</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find and sketch the level curve of when <m>c=1</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set <m>f(x,y)=c</m> and solve for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The level curve is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>.</p>
        <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-fun5b-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-2,-2,2,2)">
                    <circle center="(0,0)" radius="1" thickness="1"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph is the circle x^2+y^2=1.">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        <solution><p>Setting <m>f(x,y)=1</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=1</m>.</p>
          <p>This implies <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, which describes the unit circle centered at the origin.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find and sketch the level curve of when <m>c=4</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set <m>f(x,y)=c</m> and solve for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The level curve is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>.</p>
        <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-fun5c-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-2,-2,2,2)">
                    <circle center="(0,0)" radius="2" thickness="1"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph is the circle x^2+y^2=4.">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        <solution><p>Setting <m>f(x,y)=4</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=4</m>.</p>
          <p>This implies <m>x^2+y^2=16</m>, which describes the circle centered at the origin with radius 4.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the limit as <m>(x,y) \to (3,-4)</m> of <m>f(x,y)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the limit, since the function is continuous at the point, 
          substitute the point into the function.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (3,-4)} f(x,y)=5</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>we can substitute the point into the function since <m>f(3,-4)</m> is defined:</p>
          <p><m>f(3,-4)=\sqrt{3^2+(-4)^2}=\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>Find the limit as <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(x,y)=\frac{xy}{x^2+y^4}</m>.</p></statement>
      <hint><p>Since the function is indeterminate at the origin, approach along different 
        paths to determine the limit.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} \frac{xy}{x^2+y^4}</m> does not exist.</p></answer>
      <solution><p>Approaching the origin along the path <m>y=x</m>:</p>
        <p><m>\lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x \cdot x}{x^2+x^4} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x^2}{x^2(1+x^2)} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{1}{1+x^2} = 1</m>.</p>
        <p>Approaching the origin along the path <m>y=x^2</m>:</p>
        <p><m>\lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x \cdot x^2}{x^2+(x^2)^4} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x^3}{x^2+x^8} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x}{1+x^6} = 0</m>.</p>
        <p>Since the limits along different paths are not equal, the limit does not exist.</p></solution>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
